CENTERED	0004	615	237	1747	275	Throughout most of the Late Pennsylvanian (late Virgilian) and Early 
CENTERED	0004	615	286	1745	325	Permian (Wolfcampian), crinoids reach their lowest numbers in both 
CENTERED	0004	615	336	1750	374	abundance and diversity in the North American Midcontinent. Part of 
CENTERED	0004	614	386	1746	424	this observation may be based on collecting bias, as collecting efforts 
CENTERED	0004	615	435	1746	474	have been focused mainly in the older Late Pennsylvanian (Missou-
CENTERED	0004	614	485	1745	522	rian), where crinoids are more abundant and more diverse. In addition 
CENTERED	0004	614	535	1745	574	to systematic treatment of the sample, we have attempted to charac-
CENTERED	0004	614	584	1745	622	terize the epifauna observed on these crinoids and to provide evi-
CENTERED	0004	614	633	1745	672	dence for parasitic, commensal, and predatory relations among crinoids 
CENTERED	0004	614	683	1745	721	and their associated flora and fauna. We have observed 34 species 
CENTERED	0004	614	732	1744	771	that are assigned to 26 genera. <i>Adacrinus </i>edema Pabian and Rushlau 
CENTERED	0004	614	782	1746	820	new species and <i>Glaukosocrinus berryi </i>Pabian and Rushlau new spe-
